{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a optimization task involving a directed acyclic graph of operations to minimize total cost. I will delegate the algorithmic strategy and the implementation to specialized helpers.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "algorithm_designer",
      "instructions": "Analyze the cost function C = sum((tx - fx) + (ty - fy)). Note that this is equivalent to the sum of Manhattan distances of the edges in the construction tree. Since we start at (0,0) and must reach all (ai, bi), the minimum possible cost C is achieved by finding a Minimum Spanning Tree or a Steiner Tree structure that respects the monotonicity constraint (tx >= fx and ty >= fy). Propose a greedy or MST-based strategy that ensures every target is reachable from (0,0) while minimizing the sum of coordinate differences. Consider sorting targets by x then y to simplify the construction."
    },
    {
      "label": "python_implementer",
      "instructions": "Write a complete main.py script based on the strategy provided by the algorithm designer. The script must: 1. Read N and the N target coordinates from stdin. 2. Implement the chosen algorithm to generate a sequence of operations (from_x, from_y, to_x, to_y). 3. Ensure the sequence is valid (the 'from' beverage must have been created previously or be the starting (0,0)). 4. Print the number of operations m, followed by m lines of the operations. 5. Ensure no extra text, markdown, or debug info is printed to stdout. Use a simple, robust approach like sorting targets by x and y and connecting each target to a previously created target that minimizes the Manhattan distance while satisfying the monotonicity constraint."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the algorithmic strategy from the designer with the implementation from the coder to produce a single, valid main.py file that minimizes the cost C."
}

